commit 7ef9937b4fe8a412b2fcd3679b53b305f0f764fb
Author: Jackie Liu <liuyun01@kylinos.cn>

mm/mempolicy: fix memory leak in weighted_interleave_auto_store()

This commit fixes a memory leak in weighted_interleave_auto_store
when a user writes "false" to the auto sysfs interface and the current
mode is already manual.

> diff --git a/mm/mempolicy.c b/mm/mempolicy.c
> index 51f298cfc33b..9e723093af72 100644
> --- a/mm/mempolicy.c
> +++ b/mm/mempolicy.c
> @@ -3722,6 +3722,7 @@ static ssize_t weighted_interleave_auto_store(struct kobject *kobj,
>  			goto update_wi_state;
>  		if (input == old_wi_state->mode_auto) {
>  			mutex_unlock(&wi_state_lock);
> +			kfree(new_wi_state);
>  			return count;
>  		}

While this fixes the memory leak when input is false, does this code still
leak the active wi_state when the user writes true?

Looking at the rest of weighted_interleave_auto_store(), old_wi_state is
initialized to NULL and is only fetched inside the if (!input) block. When
input is true, that block is skipped, leaving old_wi_state as NULL.

The code then unconditionally overwrites the global wi_state pointer:

update_wi_state:
	rcu_assign_pointer(wi_state, new_wi_state);
	mutex_unlock(&wi_state_lock);
	if (old_wi_state) {
		synchronize_rcu();
		kfree(old_wi_state);
	}

Because old_wi_state is NULL when input is true, the cleanup path is bypassed,
and the previously active struct weighted_interleave_state is leaked. This
could allow a repeatable memory leak by writing '1' to the sysfs file in a
loop.

Would it make sense to fetch old_wi_state unconditionally before evaluating
input? This would address the leak when writing true, and also allow your
early-return fix to apply to the input == true case as well.

